            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#TA">
                <p>To the parents of Gnaeus Domitius Piso. (This burial) spot was donated publicly, 10 feet in breadth.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary" resp="#AA">
                <p>Bivona (1994) suggests that given his name, and that the land for the tomb was assigned to his parents, Cn. Domitius Piso must have been a notable figure in Thermae Himeraeae. There are numerous literary and epigraphic attestations to the gens Domitia across Sicily from a broad period (Republican-4th century CE). Notable, particularly, is a Domitius Himeraeus from Thermae Himeraeae (<ref target="http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic000169">ISic000169</ref>).</p>
            </div>
